                                                <p><name type="person">Private Francis L. Whitney</name>, <name type="organization">Co. B, 36th
                                                                Massachusetts Volunteers</name>, aged 24 years, was
                                                                wounded at the battle of <name type="BATTLE" key="263">Cold Harbor</name>, <date type="injury" when="1864-06-03">June 3d, 1864</date>, by a conoidal ball, which fractured the
                                                  external angle of the right orbit and the
                                                  zygomatic arch, passed inward and downward, and
                                                  lodged behind the right masseter muscle. He was
                                                  admitted to the hospital of the 2d division, Ninth
                                                  Corps, and on <date type="transfer" when="1864-06-09">June 9th</date> was sent to the <name type="hospital" key="172">Emory Hospital</name> at Washington. He had lost considerable blood, was anæmic, comatose, and suffered extreme
                                                  pain, moaning constantly. Hæmorrhage was arrested
                                                  by compress to the external carotid, but recurred
                                                  on <date type="operation" when="1864-06-14">the 14th</date>. The patient was placed under the
                                                  influence of ether and chloroform, when
                                                  persulphate of iron was applied to the bleeding
                                                  vessels, and the orifice plugged up with a
                                                  styptic. The ball could not be found. Hæmorrhage
                                                  recurred on <date type="operation" when="1864-06-16">June 16th, 1864</date>. The external carotid
                                                  artery was now tied a little above the omo-hyoid
                                                  muscle, and the ball was extracted from behind the
                                                  masseter. The man <date type="death" when="1864-06-16">died on the table</date> from nervous
                                                  exhaustion and anæmia. No anæsthetic had been
                                                  employed at the second operation. <name type="person">Acting Assistant
                                                    Surgeon W. A. Ensign</name>, the operator, reported the
                                                  case. </p>
                                           
                                              
                                                 
                                                
